(85, 'Public Interest Litigation Concerning Environmental Matters before Human Rights - Schall--2008.pdf', 'Public Interest Litigation Concerning Environmental Matters Before Human Rights Courts: A Promising Future Concept?', NULL, 'Christian Schall', 'This article endeavours to explain the current state of environmental public interest litigation before the three regional human rights bodies of Europe, America and Africa in the light of their constituting treaties and case law. It assesses the likely impact of the Aarhus Convention and the changing national jurisdictions on the procedural but also on the substantive rights guaranteed by these bodies. It also assesses the chances of reform to broaden access to justice in environmental matters in the European human rights system. It argues that, although national and international jurisdictions generally point towards broader access to justice, the legal systems currently employed by the European and Inter-American human rights institutions are not apt for a concept of public interest litigation.', 'page2pdf-2.1', 'iTextÂ® 5.5.9 Â©2000-2015 iText Group NV (AGPL-version); modified using iTextÂ® 7.1.3 Â©2000-2018 iText Group NV (JSTOR Michigan; licensed version)', 1065765, '10/24/2025, 5:58:27 PM', 'D:20170811193433-04\'00\'', 'D:20200913205149Z', 'eng', NULL, 1.6, b'0', b'0', b'0', b'0', b'0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Oxford University Press', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'null', b'0', '1761317907168', NULL, '2008', 'Environmental litigation - Public interest in', 'application/pdf', '2025-10-25 15:04:11', '2025-10-27 15:17:28'),
(86, 'Public Libraries and Human Rights.pdf', 'Public Libraries And Human Rights', 'Public Library Quarterly 2006.25:57-73', 'Mc Cook, Kathleen De La Peña; Katharine J. Phenix', 'Public librarians derive the philosophical and ethical principles that guide our practice from transcendent ideals which are also embodied in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. This article reviews the foundation of the U.S. public library and key documents that have characterized its development. Recent violations of human rights in U.S. libraries include closure; exclusion of the homeless; refusal to purchase Spanish-language materials; ordinances against gay pride display; and filtering. The importance of the public librarian\\\\\\\'s commitment to human rights as the ethical basis for library service is defined and discussed.', NULL, 'iText 2.1.5 (by lowagie.com)', 640670, '10/24/2025, 5:58:53 PM', 'D:20111229151205-08\'00\'', 'D:20111229151205-08\'00\'', 'null', NULL, 1.4, b'0', b'0', b'0', b'0', b'0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Public Library Quarterly', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'null', b'0', '1761317933832', 'null', '2007', 'E-books Copyrighted', 'application/pdf', '2025-10-25 15:04:11', '2025-10-27 15:20:22');
