(87, 'Race, Poverty, the Death Penalty, and the Responsibility of the Legal Profession.pdf', 'Race, Poverty, The Death Penalty, And The Responsibility Of The Legal Professon', NULL, 'Stephen B. Bright', 'There is a growing debate in the United States about the wisdom of capital punishment. Separate from the question of whether the state should kill, this debate involves issues of race, the quality of legal representation for people facing the death penalty, and the risk of executing innocent people. Are people being sentenced to death because of the crime they commited? Because of their race? The race of their victims? Their inability to hire a lawyer? Do we really have a working adversarial system? Are trials pro- ducing accurate results? How do these issues relate to the legal profession — especially for individuals who face the ultimate punishment?', 'Appligent pdfHarmony 2.0', 'Prince 12.5 (www.princexml.com)', 47689, '10/24/2025, 5:58:30 PM', 'D:20191120150336-08\'00\'', 'D:20210331160228+03\'00\'', 'en', NULL, 1.7, b'0', b'0', b'1', b'0', b'0', NULL, 'pdfHarmony 2.0 Linux Kernel 2.6 64bit Mar 13 2012 Library 9.0.1', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Seattle Journal For Social Justice', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'null', b'0', '1761317910123', NULL, '2002', 'Death Penalty in Africa (English and French), free/English', 'application/pdf', '2025-10-25 15:04:11', '2025-10-27 15:22:49'),
(88, 'Judges guarding judges investigating regional harbours for judicial independence in africa.pdf', 'Judges Guarding Judges Investigating Regional Harbours For Judicial Independence In Africa', NULL, 'Sègnonna Horace Adjolohoun', 'A body of jurisprudence is emerging in Africa\\\'s most active regional courts on the independence of national judiciaries. This article reveals that while regional case law relevantly echoes efforts by municipal courts to safeguard themselves, circumstances demonstrate that such case law requires greater contextualization across systems. In this regard, the traditional paradigm of linking independence to executive appointments does not empirically stand the test of the multiplicity of independence factors, executive-free regimes have not proved effective in safeguarding independence, and legal traditions or judicial systems have increasingly become irrelevant to the effectiveness of any independence regime. Factors that transcend the traditional determinants of executive control include the nature and functions of the court involved, and the history and background of the judicial structure of the country or region. Notably, the discussion also reveals the need to strike a critical balance between individual rights to a fair trial and inter-state directive policy towards judicial independence as set out in the African Charter.', 'Arbortext Advanced Print Publisher 10.0.1465/W Unicode', 'Acrobat Distiller 8.1.0 (Windows)', 344940, '10/24/2025, 5:58:49 PM', 'D:20230608140505+05\'30\'', 'D:20230609110157+00\'00\'', 'null', NULL, 1.3, b'0', b'0', b'0', b'0', b'0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Cambridge University Press', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'null', b'0', '1761317929352', NULL, '2023', 'eBook Samples', 'application/pdf', '2025-10-25 15:04:11', '2025-10-27 15:24:13'),
(89, 'Securing cyberspace through public-private partnership.pdf', 'Securing Cyberspace Through Public- Private Partnership: A Comparative Analysis Of Partnership Models', NULL, 'Rachel Nyswander Thomas', 'Though the term “cybersecurity” has only recently penetrated the American psyche, concern among policymakers about the need to better secure cyberspace has been intensifying for nearly two decades. The threat of cybercrime and state-sponsored attacks is growing, and cyber threats are evolving rapidly.12 Today, cybersecurity is a national priority, and public- private partnership (PPP) is understood as a vital tool in securing cyberspace. Despite the proliferation of cybersecurity PPPs over the past decade, the literature suggests that such efforts have often suffered from ill-defined goals and objectives, a lack of clearly articulated strategy, and a focus on information sharing as a goal rather than a tool. In light of such criticism, this paper asks, and seeks to answer, a foundational question: what model of PPP is most appropriate for the task of securing cyberspace? Four PPP alternatives are proposed and analyzed, from which one alternative is identified for implementation. A strategy for implementation is recommended for the chosen alternative', 'MicrosoftÂ® Word 2010', 'MicrosoftÂ® Word 2010', 732422, '10/24/2025, 5:58:29 PM', 'D:20130819165002-04\'00\'', 'D:20170403234627+03\'00\'', 'en-US', NULL, 1.5, b'0', b'0', b'1', b'0', b'0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Rachel Nyswander Thomas', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'null', b'0', '1761317909765', NULL, '2013', 'Cybersecurity and human rights', 'application/pdf', '2025-10-25 15:04:11', '2025-10-27 15:27:14'),
